success.question_text: How many people visited the house that week?
success.question_hint:
• Count the whole symbols and then the half symbols and add them together.
  • Multiply this number by the value of each symbol shown in the key.

stimulus_1.text: Damien has drawn a pictograph to show the number of people who visited a house that was for sale over a week:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Think carefully and don’t rush into answering a question and you might see an easier way. For example, in this question just count by twos through the whole graph, counting all the whole symbols, and add the three single visitors at the end.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• The median is the middle score.
  • You need to rewrite the scores in order from smallest to largest.

stimulus_1.text: Dane scored these marks in a series of spelling tests: 8, 9, 1, 6, 8, 7, 10.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

In order the scores are 1, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 10.

The median is 8.

Tip

The median is the middle score when the scores are arranged in order. If there is an odd number of scores, there will be one middle score. If there is an even number of scores, the median will be the average of the two middle scores.

success.question_text: If Chiara chooses a peg from the bucket without looking, how could the chance that it is red be described?
success.question_hint:
• There are lots of pegs but only one is red.
  • The sequence of words describing chance in order is impossible, unlikely, fifty-fifty, possible and certain.

stimulus_1.text: Chiara has these pegs in her bucket:

review_3.column_1_text:
There are 20 pegs in the bucket and only one is red.

The chance of choosing a red peg is very small, but not impossible.

The chance should be described as unlikely.

Tip

If an event is impossible, the probability is 0. If the event is certain, the probability is 1. For all other events the probability must be between 0 and 1.

success.question_hint:
• The table shows the number of each colour.
  • Read each option and check the data in the table.

stimulus_1.text: Alice recorded the colour of all the cars that went past her house in an hour, then drew up a table to show the results:

review_4.column_1_text:
The incorrect statement is ‘The number of white cars was more than three times any other single colour.’

Tip

Sometimes it is necessary to check every option in a multiple-choice question.

choice_2.label: There were twice as many red cars as black.

choice_3.label: Together there were more black and green cars than silver cars.

choice_4.label: The number of white cars was more than three times any other single colour.

success.question_text: Which of these is equal to 7? Select all possible answers.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• More than one of the options will give an answer of 7.
  • Find the range, mode, median and mean of the 6 scores.

review_2.column_1_text:
Lowest score = 3

The range, mode and median are all equal to 7.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The range is the difference between the highest and lowest score. The mode is the score with the highest frequency. The median is the middle score. The mean is the measure commonly called the average.

success.question_text:
If these results were illustrated by a sector graph, what should the angle representing Cal be?

Type the number of degrees in the box below, without the degree sign.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Data Representation and Analysis
success.question_hint:
• 100% of the sector graph is represented by an angle of 360°.
  • You need to find Cal’s percentage of the 360°.

stimulus_1.text: Gisele took a survey of people asking which contestant they each thought would win a singing contest. The results, as percentages, are shown in the table:

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• There are 7 days of the week.
  • The mean is found by adding the scores and dividing by the number of scores.

stimulus_1.text: Lucy recorded the number of snails she saw in her garden each day for a week.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The mean is another name for the measure commonly called the average. To find the mean, divide the sum of the scores by the number of scores.

success.question_text: If an apple is chosen, without looking, from the bowl, what is the probability that it is green?
success.question_hint:
• Count the number of green apples.
  • Count all the apples and write your first answer as a fraction of the second.

stimulus_2.text: A bowl holds three green and seven red apples.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The probability of an event is equal to the number of times the event occurs out of the total number of possible outcomes.

success.question_text: How many more boys preferred to ride than walk?
success.question_hint:
• There were 150 students surveyed so use subtraction to find the missing number.
  • You need to find the difference between the two numbers in the boys’ row.

stimulus_1.text: 150 students were asked whether they preferred to walk or ride their bikes to a sporting event. Some of the results are shown in the table:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Read the question carefully and make sure you answer the question that has been asked.

success.question_text: Based on these results, how many bald men would you expect in a group of 100 men?
success.question_hint:
• Count the number of dots on the graph to work out the number of males surveyed.
  • As there are 3 bald men out of this total, find this fraction of 100 men.

stimulus_1.text: A dot plot was drawn to show the result of a survey of hair colour of male shoppers at a mall:

review_3.column_1_text:
Total number shown on dot plot = 30

3 out of 30 are bald.

So based on these results 1 in 10 will be bald.

In 100 men, 10 would be expected to be bald.

Tip

If basing results on a previous survey, it is important to consider whether that is a reasonable thing to do. For example, in a survey of hair colour like in this question if the surveyed group were school students the results would be different to a group of senior citizens.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Data Representation and Analysis
success.question_hint:
• You need to first understand the diagram, e.g. Dan scored more goals than Henry because the arrow goes from Dan towards Henry.
  • Find the person who does not have any arrows towards himself.

stimulus_1.text: A diagram was drawn to show the result when five boys compared the number of goals they had scored that season:

review_3.column_1_text:
Ross scored more goals than both Henry and Dan.

Mitch scored more goals than Ross and also more goals than Ben.

Mitch scored the most goals.

Tip

Read the information carefully.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• You need a third column where you have multiplied the score by the frequency.
  • The mean is the total of the third column divided by the total of the frequencies.

stimulus_1.text: The marks scored by a class in a quick quiz were placed into a frequency distribution table:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The frequency is the number of times a score occurs. Multiplying each score by its frequency, then adding these products, gives the total of all the scores. The mean is the result of dividing that total by the total frequency. This question could have been done by adding a ‘fx’ column to the table (f is the frequency and x the score so the numbers in the fx column are the result of multiplying the frequency by the score).The mean is the sum of the fx column divided by the sum of the f column.

success.question_text: Which of these is most likely to occur?
success.question_hint:
• The outcomes of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6 are equally likely.
  • Dividing 50 by the number of outcomes gives an estimate of the total number of times each outcome appears.

success.question_text:
How tall (in centimetres) is the coach?

Type the number of centimetres in the box below without the cm sign, e.g. 7 for 7 cm.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• Work out the total height of the players.
  • Subtract this from the total height of the players plus the coach.

stimulus_2.text: The mean height of five players in a basketball team is 201 cm. The mean height of the five players and the coach is 196 cm.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The product of the mean and the number of scores is the total of all the scores.

If Kelly sells six bracelets at the market, how much profit does she make?

Type the number, not the $ sign, e.g. for $2 type 2.
success.question_hint:
• The profit is the Return minus Cost.
  • Starting at 6 on the horizontal scale, look up to find where the red graph crosses the 6 and subtract the value where the blue line crosses the 6.

stimulus_1.text: Kelly makes bracelets and sells them at a market. The graph shows the cost to make the bracelets and the return (the amount Kelly receives) from sales of the bracelets:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Read all the information carefully. Sometimes information will appear in the preliminary part of the question.
